the horror–and the unintended humour–of life in a rigidly bureaucratic society, a theme of universal interest. The Silenced Theatre is the only detailed study of this dynamic and modern national theatre. This book will help to preserve Czech drama and create an awareness of its important role in Western literaturea role it continues to play even in exile from its homeland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCzech dramay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDramatists, Czechy20th centuryvBiography. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBlazek, Vratislav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanëk, Oldfich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHrubin, Frantisek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarvas, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKundera, Milan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandovsky, Pavel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahler, Zdenëk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPavlicek, Frantisek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUhde, Milan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVostrá, Aleña, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148759593740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487595937423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487595937.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_